'''Kaman-Kalehöyük''' is a multi-period [[archaeological site]] in [[Kırşehir Province]], [[Turkey]], around 100&nbsp;km south east of [[Ankara]] 6&nbsp;km east of the town center of Kaman.<ref name=AncientAnatolia1>{{cite book|last1=Steadman|first1=Sharon R.|last2=McMahon|first2=Gregory|title=The Oxford Handbook of Ancient Anatolia: (10,000 - 323 BCE)|date=2011|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-537614-2|page=1095|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ND_CE9If3kC&pg=PA1095#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=17 May 2015}}</ref> It is a [[Tell (archaeology)|tell]] or mound site that was occupied during the [[Bronze Age]], [[Iron Age]] and [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] periods. Since 1986 it has been investigated by archaeologists from the [[Middle Eastern Culture Center in Japan]].

In 2005, [[metallurgy|metallurgical]] analysis by Hideo Akanuma of iron fragments found at Kaman-Kalehöyük in 1994 and dating to ''c''. 1800 BCE revealed that some of these fragments were  composed of carbon [[steel]]; these currently form the world's earliest known evidence for steel manufacture.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Akanuma|first=H.|title=The significance of the composition of excavated iron fragments taken from Stratum III at the site of Kaman-Kalehöyük, Turkey |journal=Anatolian Archaeological Studies |volume=14 |pages=147–158 |year=2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Ironware piece unearthed from Turkey found to be oldest steel|url=http://www.hindu.com/thehindu/holnus/001200903261611.htm|accessdate=2009-03-27|location=Chennai, India|work=The Hindu|date=2009-03-26}}</ref>

