{{clear}}

==Prefixes==
* '''A''' – ([[Romanian language|Romanian]]) "son of"
* '''Ab''' – ([[Welsh language|Welsh]], [[Breton language|Breton]]) "son of"<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/wales/history/sites/themes/society/family_03_welshnaming.shtml|title=BBC Wales  - History - Themes  - Welsh naming|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-04-28}}</ref>
* '''Af''', '''Av''' - ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]) "of"
* '''Ap''' – ([[Welsh language|Welsh]]) "son of"<ref name=":0" />
* '''Abu''' – ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]) "father of";<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2006/07/abu_ibn_and_bin_oh_my.html|title=Abu, Ibn, and Bin, Oh My!|last=Engber|first=Daniel|date=2006-07-03|work=Slate|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref> also used in Hebrew prior to 1300 BC{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Al''' – (Arabic) "the"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/explainer/2006/06/whats_up_with_al.html|title=What's Up With "Al-"?|last=Engber|first=Daniel|date=2006-06-28|work=Slate|access-date=2018-04-28|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339}}</ref>
*'''Ālam'''-(Persian) "world"
* '''Bar''' – ([[Aramaic language|Aramaic]]) "son of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Bath''', '''bat''' – ([[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]) "daughter of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Ben''', '''bin''', '''ibn''' – ([[Arabic language|Arabic]] and [[Hebrew language|Hebrew]]) "son of"<ref name=":1" />
* '''Bet''' – ([[Arabic language|Arabic]] from "Beyt") "house of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Bint''' – ([[Arabic language|Arabic]]) "daughter of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Da''' – ([[Italian Language|Italian]]) "from, of"; ([[Portuguese Language|Portuguese]]) "from the" (before a feminine singular noun){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Das''' – ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) "from the, of the", preceding a feminine plural noun{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''De''' – ([[Italian language|Italian]], [[French language|French]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]], [[Portuguese language|Portuguese]], [[Filipinos|Filipino]]) "of"; indicates region of origin, often a sign of nobility; in Spanish-speaking countries a married woman will sometimes append  her name with "de XXXX" {{citation needed|date=September 2015}}where "XXXX" is her husband's last name; (Dutch) "the"
* '''Degli''' – ([[Italian language|Italian]]) "of the", preceding a masculine plural noun starting with either ''sp, sc, ps, z, gn'' or ''st''.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Dele''', '''Del''' – Southern French, [[Filipinos|Filipino]] and Occitan, equivalent of '''Du'''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Della''' – ([[Italian language|Italian]]) "of the", preceding a feminine singular noun{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Der''' – (Western [[Armenian language|Armenian]]) "son/daughter of a priest"; (German) "the" (masculine nominative), "of the" (feminine genitive){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Di''' – ([[Italian language|Italian]], [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) "son of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Dos''' – ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) "from the, of the", preceding a masculine plural noun{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Du''' – ([[French language|French]]) "of the", preceding a masculine singular noun{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''E''' – ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) "and", between surnames (Maria Eduarda de Canto '''e''' Mello){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''El''' – ([[Arabic]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]) "the"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Fetch''', '''Vetch''' –  – [Welsh] "daughter of"
* '''Fitz''' – (Irish, from Norman French) "son of", from Latin "filius", "son" (mistakenly thought to mean illegitimate son, because of its use for certain illegitimate sons of English kings){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''i''' – ([[Catalan language|Catalan]]) "and", always in lowercase, used to identify both surnames (Antoni Gaudí '''i''' Cornet)<ref name="iCatala">{{cite web | url = http://slg.uib.cat/gabinets/go/arxiu_consultes/Normativa.cid202242 | title = Normativa | publisher = Universitat Illes Balears}}</ref>
* '''Kil''', '''Gil''' – (English, Irish, Scottish) "son of" "servant of" or "devotee of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''La''' – (Italian, French, Spanish) "the", feminine singular{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Le''' – (Northern French) "the", masculine singular{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Lu''' – (Latin, Roman) "Master"
* '''M'/Mac/Mc/Mck/Mhic/Mic''' – (Irish, Scottish and Manx Gaelic) "son". Both ''Mac'' and ''Mc'' are sometimes written M<sup>ac</sup> and M<sup>c</sup> (with superscript ''ac'' or ''c''). In some names, ''Mc'' is pronounced ''Mac''.
*'''Mala''' – ([[Kurdish language|Kurdish]]) "House of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Na''' – ณ ([[Thai language|Thai]]) "at"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Neder''' – (Swedish) "lower", "under"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Nic''', '''Ni''' – (Irish, Scottish) "daughter of", from (Irish)"Inion"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Nin''' – (Serbian){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Nord''', '''Norr''' – ([[German language|German]], [[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]) "north"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Ny''' – ([[Swedish language|Swedish]], [[Danish language|Danish]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]) "new"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''O/Ua/Ui'''' – (Irish, Scottish and Manx Gaelic) "grandson of", "descendant of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Öfver''' – ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]) "upper", "over" (archaic spelling){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Ost''' (German), '''öst''', '''öster''' ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]), '''øst''' ([[Danish language|Danish]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]) – "east"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Över''' – ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]) "upper", "over"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Öz''' – (Turkish) "pure"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Pour''' – (Persian) "son of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Stor''' – ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]) "large"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Söder''' – ([[Swedish language|Swedish]]), '''sønder''' ([[Danish language|Danish]]), "south"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Ter''' – (Dutch) "at the"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Ter''' – (Eastern Armenian) "son/daughter of a Priest"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Tre''' – ([[Cornwall|Cornish]]) "farm of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Van''' – (Dutch) "of", "from" {{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Väst–''', '''Väster''' – (Swedish) "west"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Vest''' – ([[Danish language|Danish]], [[Norwegian language|Norwegian]]) "west"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''von''' – (German) "of"; a sign of nobility.{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* '''Woj -''' (Polish) "province"
* '''zu''' - (German) "at"; a sign of nobility, sometimes in the combination '''von and zu'''

==Suffixes==

* -'''a''',  -'''ya''' [[Kurdish language|Kurdish]] means "of" (female) (by two surnames){{clarify|date=June 2015}}{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''a'''- ([[Frisian languages|Frisian]]) "One of the good guys", could be -ma, -stra, -ta. Frisians took the oath of the Free Frisians {{citation needed|date=September 2015}}screaming 'Better dead than a slave' after which they could get their new surnames (see [[Eala Frya Fresena]]).
* -'''à''' (Catalan){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ac''' ([[Croatian (language)|Croatian]], [[Serbian language|Serbian]], [[Slovenian (language)|Slovenian]], Southern French){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ach''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] /[[Belarusian Latin alphabet|Belarusian Latin]]: -'''ač'''/){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
** -'''acz''' ([[Polish language|Polish]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''aei''' ([[Persian language|Persian]]) (See -i) for words that end in the long vowel ''A''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ago''' ([[Russian language|Russian]]) (e.g. Zhivago){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''aitis''' ([[Lithuanian language|Lithuanian]]) "son of"{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
** -'''aitė''' (Lithuanian) signifies an unmarried female{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
*** -'''aty''' Americanized form{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''aj''' ([[Albanian language|Albanian]]) (pronounced AY; meaning  “of the" ) It denotes the name of the family, which mostly comes from the male founder of the family, but also from a place, as in, Lash-aj (from the village Lashaj of Kastrat, MM, Shkoder).  It is likely that its ancient form, still found in MM, was an [i] in front of the last name, as in ‘Déda i Lékajve’  (Déd of Lekës).  For ease of use, the [i] in front of the last name, and the ending _ve, were dropped.  If the last name ends in [a], then removing the [j] would give the name of the patriarch or the place, as in, Grudaj - j = Gruda (place in MM).  Otherwise, removing the whole ending [aj] yields the name of founder or place of origin, as in Lekaj - aj = Lek(ë).  Since the names are found most commonly in Malsi e Madhe (North) and Labëri (South), it is likely that this linguistic feature is very old.  It must have been lost as a result of foreign influences brought into Albania by the invaders.  {{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ak''' ([[Polish language|Polish]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]], [[Croatian (language)|Croatian]], [[Slovenian (language)|Slovenian]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]], [[Montenegrin language|Montenegrin]], [[Sorbian languages|Sorbian]]) See ''-ák'' for its [[Slovak language|Slovak]] meaning.<ref name="AkSlovak">{{cite web | url = http://www.pitt.edu/~votruba/qsonhist/slovaklastnamesfromfirstnames.html | title = Last Names in -ák | last = Votruba | first = Martin | work = Slovak Studies Program | publisher = University of Pittsburgh}}</ref>
** -'''ák''' ([[Czech language|Czech]], [[Slovak language|Slovak]]) In [[Slovak language|Slovak]], ''-ák'' means "pertaining to" or merely creates a noun, and its two other versions are ''-iak'' and ''-ak''.<ref name="AkSlovak"/>
*-'''al''' ([[Nepali language|Nepali]]) denotes for village of origin (for e.g; [[Khanal]], [[Dhakal]], [[Dahal]], [[Rijal]], etc.)
* -'''an''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]]) (e.g. Ruban){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''an''' ([[Romanian language|Romanian]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''án''' (Spanish){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''and''' (French){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ange''' (French) from Germanic ''-ing''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ano''' ([[Italian language|Italian]]) feminine '''-ana''' "of or from [a locality]"; from Latin ''-ānus, -āna''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''anu''' (Romanian){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ár''' ([[Slovak language|Slovak]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''ář''' ([[Czech language|Czech]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''arz''' ([[Polish language|Polish]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''au''' (-'''aw''') ([[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] /[[Belarusian Latin alphabet|Belarusian Latin]]: -'''aŭ'''/) equivalent to Russian -'''ov'''{{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''auskas'''/-'''iauskas''' (Lithuanian for the Polish -'''owski''', -'''ewski''', Belarusian -'''ouski''', -'''euski''' /[[Belarusian Latin alphabet|Belarusian Latin]]: -'''oŭski''', -'''eŭski'''/){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
* -'''awan''' ([[Urdu]]){{citation needed|date=September 2015}}
