{{distinguish|Qasr al-Banat|Qasr el Banat, Lebanon|Gasr Banat}} {{Infobox ancient site |name = Qasr el Banat |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = |alt = |caption = |map_type = Egypt |map_alt = |map_size = 200 |location = between [[Qift]] and [[Al-Qusayr, Egypt]], [[Egypt]] |region = |coordinates = {{coord|28.667|30.867|display=inline}} |type = [[Fort]] |part_of = |length ={{convert|40|m|ft}} |width ={{convert|33|m|ft}} |area = |height = |builder = |material = Stone |built = |abandoned = |epochs = |cultures = [[Ancient Rome]] |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |excavations = |archaeologists = |condition = |ownership = |management = |public_access = |website = |notes = }} '''Qasr el Banat''' is an [[Ancient Roman]] [[fort]] located between [[Qift]] and [[Al-Qusayr, Egypt|Al-Qusayr]] in [[Egypt]].<ref name="Alston1998">{{cite book|author=Richard Alston|title=Soldier and Society in Roman Egypt: A Social History|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OIqHgAkip4YC&pg=RA1-PA194|accessdate=31 October 2012|date=6 May 1998|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-415-18606-3|pages=1–}}</ref><ref name="egyptian antiquities in the nile valley">{{cite book|title=egyptian antiquities in the nile valley|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QwQOAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA866|accessdate=31 October 2012|publisher=Taylor & Francis|pages=866–|id=GGKEY:GFAW834EXZU}}</ref>
The fort measures {{convert|40|m|ft}} by {{convert|33|m|ft}}. Inscriptions found nearby have been dated to the reigns of the emperors [[Augustus]] and [[Hadrian]].<ref name="Alston1998"/>
